Feature Selection¶

To choose the best covariates to use in our model, I'll be using sklearn's SelectFromModel and the ExtraTreesClassifier, which uses Gini importance to find the feature importance. I chose SelectFromModel using the ExtraTreesClassifier because it's simple but efficient. Since I'll be using the same features across all of my models I'll find them outside of the pipelines to cut down on processing time and to see what variables are chosen and their levels of importance. Feature selection is important to prevent overfitting and for quicker processing.

In [517]:
clf = ExtraTreesClassifier(n_estimators=1000)
clf = clf.fit(train_no_lbl, labels.total_cases)
model = SelectFromModel(clf, prefit=True)
X_new = model.transform(train_no_lbl)

Modeling¶

GaussianNB¶

The Gaussian Naive Bayes classifier uses Bayes theorem of there being "naive" independence between features. The accuracy score, mean absolute error, and mean squared error are as follows:

In [501]:
#using StandardScaler to standardize the data
pipe = make_pipeline(StandardScaler(copy=True, with_mean=True, with_std=True), GaussianNB())

#there are no hyperparameters for GaussianNB
param_grid = { 
}

grid = GridSearchCV(pipe, param_grid, verbose=0, cv=folds, return_train_score=True) 
grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

predictions_1 = grid.predict(X_test)

print('Accuracy score: ' + str(accuracy_score(y_test, predictions_1)))
acc.append(accuracy_score(y_test, predictions_1))

print('MAE: ' + str(metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_test, predictions_1)))
MAE.append(metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_test, predictions_1))

print('MSE: ' + str(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions_1)))

mdl.append('GaussianNB')

KNeighborsClassifier¶

The k-Nearest Neighbor classifier finds similar cases to the given data case and then returns the average of the most similar data cases. The accuracy score, mean absolute error, and mean squared error are as follows:

In [503]:
# Scale values to use KNeighbors
pipe = make_pipeline(MinMaxScaler(), KNeighborsClassifier())

# Define a grid to search through
param_grid = {'kneighborsclassifier__n_neighbors':range(1, 100),
              'kneighborsclassifier__weights':["uniform", "distance"]}

# Perform a  grid search of your pipeline
grid = GridSearchCV(pipe, param_grid, verbose=0, cv=folds, return_train_score=True) 
grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

predictions_3 = grid.predict(X_test)

print('Accuracy score: ' + str(accuracy_score(y_test, predictions_3)))
acc.append(accuracy_score(y_test, predictions_3))

print('MAE: ' + str(metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_test, predictions_3)))
MAE.append(metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_test, predictions_3))

print('MSE: ' + str(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions_3)))
MSE.append(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions_3))

mdl.append('KNeighborsClassifier')

XGBClassifier¶

Gradient boost classifiers also build desicion trees, but do so one at a time so new trees can correct errors previous trees may have made. The accuracy score, mean absolute error, and mean squared error are as follows:

In [506]:
pipe = make_pipeline(XGBClassifier())

param_grid = {"xgbclassifier__max_depth": [5],
              "xgbclassifier__min_child_weight": [4],
              "xgbclassifier__gamma": [ 0.0],
             }

grid = GridSearchCV(pipe, param_grid, verbose=0, cv=folds, return_train_score=True) 
grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

predictions_5 = grid.predict(X_test)

print('Accuracy score: ' + str(accuracy_score(y_test, predictions_5)))
acc.append(accuracy_score(y_test, predictions_5))

print('MAE: ' + str(metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_test, predictions_5)))
MAE.append(metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_test, predictions_5))

print('MSE: ' + str(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions_5)))

mdl.append('XGBClassifier')

From these graphs, you can see that the GaussianNB predictions aren't matching the actual values as well as the other graphs. The predictions from RandomForest match the outliers from the actual values quite well, which probably contributes to their lower mean squared error score. Finally, XGboost which had the highest accuracy score seems to be matching the predictions with their actual values quite well.

For the DengAI competition, I haven't been able to check the scores of all my models because of the submission limitation, but so far the GaussianNB model is in the lead.
